On Tuesday, September 1, the Board of Education approved the following timeline for transition to in-person learning. Schools will be sending out a communication to parents next week regarding the AM/PM hybrid schedules and student cohorts assigned in each cohort. These schedules will be posted on Friday, September 11. Visit the Santee School District website (www.santeesd.net), for the most current information.

STUDENT MEAL SERVICE NOTICE/UPDATE

Starting September 1, 2020 meal charging policies may revert to charging for meals based on student eligibility. Students attending Project SAFE will be served lunch daily and provided a breakfast for the next morning.

We encourage you to apply for free or reduced meals. If you qualify for free or reduced meals, you may qualify for free internet and or other helpful services. Online applications are also available at:

http://www.schoolnutritionandfitness.com/index.php?sid=2707152252113767&page=lunchapps

NEED BOOKS? The Santee School District is excited to announce that we have FREE books for K-8 students! Stop by the District Office (9625 Cuyamaca St) M-F from 8-3 and grab some books to read with your kiddos. 📚

Thank you to the San Diego Book Project for their donation. “The purpose of the book project is to promote literacy, and your efforts, particularly during these trying times, are invaluable,” said Mike Meaney who runs this project.

post_text:
PUBLIC NOTICE: Youth ages 12 to 25 are invited to get a free heart screening on Sunday, November 4 at Valhalla High School between 9 am and 3 pm.

The screening is offered by the Eric Paredes Save A Life Foundation. Heart screenings are not a part of annual checkups or pre-participation sports physicals, even though most heart conditions have no warning signs or unrecognized symptoms — which is why Eric’s Foundation screens for free.

Register at epsavealife.org/register/ and download a screening packet that you will complete and bring to the event. Walk-ins are also accepted after 10 a.m. and paperwork is available onsite if online registration is not possible. Screenings take less than an hour. Parents need not be present for youth who have a signed and completed screening packet. Parents will be contacted by our medical director to apprise them if a cardiac abnormality is detected.

Students wear t-shirt, sweatpants or sports shorts to the screening. Girls wear a sports bra.

PUBLIC NOTICE: Youth ages 12 to 25 are invited to get a free heart screening on Sunday, November 4 at Valhalla High School between 9 am and 3 pm.

The screening is offered by the Eric Paredes Save A Life Foundation. Heart screenings are not a part of annual checkups or pre-participation sports physicals, even though most heart conditions have no warning signs or unrecognized symptoms — which is why Eric’s Foundation screens for free.

Register at epsavealife.org/register/ and download a screening packet that you will complete and bring to the event. Walk-ins are also accepted after 10 a.m. and paperwork is available onsite if online registration is not possible. Screenings take less than an hour. Parents need not be present for youth who have a signed and completed screening packet. Parents will be contacted by our medical director to apprise them if a cardiac abnormality is detected.

Students wear t-shirt, sweatpants or sports shorts to the screening. Girls wear a sports bra.
